    <statement><p>Simplify the following expressions, and if applicable, write the restricted domain on the simplified expression.</p>
<p><ol label="a.">
<li>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{t+4}{t+4}}=}</m> <fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{t+4}{4+t}}=}</m> <fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0002"/></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{t-4}{t-4}}=}</m> <fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0003"/></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{t-4}{4-t}}=}</m> <fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0004"/></p>
</li>
</ol></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>1, t\ne -4</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>1, t\ne -4</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>1, t\ne 4</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>-1, t\ne 4</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p><ol label="a.">
<li>
<p><m>\displaystyle{    \begin{aligned}
    {\frac{t+4}{t+4}} \amp = {1, t\ne -4}
    \end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factor <m>t+4</m> was crossed out, <m>-4</m> is not in the domain. So the answer is <m>{1, t\ne -4}</m>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\displaystyle{    \begin{aligned}[t]
    {\frac{t+4}{4+t}} \amp = \frac{{t+4}}{{t+4}} \\
    \amp = {1, t\ne -4}
    \end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factor <m>t+4</m> was crossed out, <m>-4</m> is not in the domain. So the answer is <m>{1, t\ne -4}</m>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\displaystyle{    \begin{aligned}
    {\frac{t-4}{t-4}} \amp = {1, t\ne 4}
    \end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factor <m>t-4</m> was crossed out, <m>4</m> is not in the domain. So the answer is <m>{1, t\ne 4}</m>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\displaystyle{    \begin{aligned}[t]
    {\frac{t-4}{4-t}} \amp = \frac{{t-4}}{-(t-4)} \\
    \amp = \frac{1}{-1} \\
    \amp = {-1, t\ne 4}
    \end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factor <m>t-4</m> was crossed out, <m>4</m> is not in the domain. So the answer is <m>{-1, t\ne 4}</m>.</p>
</li>
</ol></p>
</solution>
